\begin_layout Subsection
Dynamical Mean Field Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Systems in Equilibrium 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dynamical Mean Field Theory is a method to solve a lattice problem with
 many degrees of freedom by mapping it to an impurity problem consisting
 of a single correlated site embedded in an uncorrelated bath.
 The bath is formed by the residual sites of the lattice and the hybridization
 between the impurity and the bath (the dynamical mean field) is the function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\Delta(\omega)}$
\end_inset

.
 It resembles the exchange of particles with the rest of the lattice and
 must be determined self consistently as a functional of the lattice Greens
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{G(\omega)}$
\end_inset

.
 The key approximation in DMFT is the local nature of the lattice self energy
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{\Sigma_{ij}^{lat}(\omega)\backsimeq\delta_{ij}\Sigma^{imp}(\omega)}
\]

\end_inset

that justifies the mapping.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In equilibrium all functions depend only on time-differences and can be
 expressed by their Fourier transforms.
 For time-dependent systems (e.g.
 an electric-field-driven lattice system) they become two-times objects
 and incorporate the overall temporal evolution of the system as well as
 quantum fluctuations.
 In the following the DMFT equations for systems in equilibrium (an extension
 to time-dependend systems follows later) will be presented.
 The simplest model for the description of strongly correlated systems is
 the single band Hubbard model representing a collection of single orbital
 atoms placed at the nodes of a crystal lattice
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{H_{Hub}=-\sum_{\langle i,j\rangle,\sigma}v_{ij}d_{i\sigma}^{\dagger}d_{j\sigma}+\sum_{i}U(d_{i\uparrow}^{\dagger}d_{i\uparrow}-\frac{1}{2})(d_{i\downarrow}^{\dagger}d_{i\downarrow}-\frac{1}{2})}.
\]

\end_inset

The operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d_{i\uparrow}^{\dagger}[d_{i\uparrow}]}$
\end_inset

 create[destroy] an electron with spin 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 in an Wannier orbital at a crystal site i, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 is the hopping between neighbouring sites (it depends on the overlap of
 neighbouring orbitals) and U is the local Coulomb interaction between electrons.
 With the approximation that the lattice self energy is local in space one
 is able to compute the local Greens function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{G_{ii}^{\sigma}(t-t^{\prime})=-i\langle\mathcal{T}d_{i\sigma}(t)d_{i\sigma}^{\dagger}(t^{\prime})\rangle}$
\end_inset

 from an effective impurity model described by the following action 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{\mathcal{\mathrm{S=i\int_{c}dtUn_{\uparrow}(t)n_{\downarrow}(t)-i\sum_{\sigma}\int_{c}dtdt^{\prime}d_{\sigma}^{\dagger}(t)\mathrm{\bigtriangleup}(t-t^{\prime})d_{\sigma}(t^{\prime})}}}.
\]

\end_inset

From here on the spin index will be supressed for simplicity.
 The impurity self energy is defined via the Dyson equation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{\mathrm{\mathrm{G_{ii}^{-1}(\omega)=}\omega+\mu-\mathrm{\bigtriangleup}(\omega)-\varSigma^{imp}(\omega)}}
\]

\end_inset

and will be used to obtain the lattice Greens function 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{\mathrm{G_{ij}^{-1}(\omega)=\delta_{ij}[}\omega+\mu-\varSigma_{ii}(\omega)]-v_{ij}}.
\]

\end_inset

In real space this means that all non-local components of the lattice self
 energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\varSigma_{ij}(\omega)}$
\end_inset

 are neglected and the local component is approximated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\varSigma^{imp}(\omega)}$
\end_inset

.
 For a translationally invariant system (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathrm{\varSigma_{ii}(\omega)\equiv\varSigma(\omega)}}$
\end_inset

) one averages over the whole Brillouin zone to get the on-site component
 of the lattice Green function (which is referred to as the self-consistency
 condition)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{\mathrm{G_{ii}(\omega)=\frac{1}{L}\sum_{k}G_{k}(\omega)}=\frac{1}{L}\sum_{k}\frac{1}{\omega+\mu+\varSigma(\omega)-\epsilon_{k}}},
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{k}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 the momentum resolved Greens function, L the number of lattice sites and
 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{k}$
\end_inset

 the dispersion relation of the non-interacting tight binding band 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{\epsilon_{k}=\sum_{j}v_{ij}exp^{ik(R_{i}-R_{j})}.}
\]

\end_inset

Instead of performing the k-summation one can integrate over the local,
 non-interacting Density of states 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D(\epsilon)=\frac{1}{L}\sum_{k}\delta(\epsilon-\epsilon_{k})}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{\mathrm{G_{ii}(\omega)=}\int\frac{D(\epsilon)}{\omega+\mu+\varSigma(\omega)-\epsilon_{k}}}.
\]

\end_inset

The self-consistency condition relates for each frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\omega}$
\end_inset

 the dynamical mean field to the local Green's function.
 This functional relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{G[\Delta]}$
\end_inset

 provides a closed set of equations to determine 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{G}$
\end_inset

.
 This can be done by an iterative procedure that does not depend on the
 initial guess for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will focus on the Hubbard model for a Bethe lattice in the limit of infinite
 dimensions, where DMFT becomes exact.
 With its semicircular Density of states 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{D(\epsilon)=\frac{1}{2\pi v_{0}^{2}}\sqrt{4v_{0}-\epsilon^{2}}}\label{semicircularDOS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

it relates the Greens function to the hybridization function in the simple
 way
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\Delta(\omega)=v_{0}^{2}G(\omega).}\label{eq:selfconsistency}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Systems out of Equilibrium 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To capture non-equilibirum physics one must extend the dynamical mean field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(\omega)$
\end_inset

 to a time-dependent field 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(t,t')$
\end_inset

.
 In the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $d\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 the self energy is local in space 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma_{ij}(t,t')=\delta_{ij}\Sigma_{i}(t,t')
\]

\end_inset

and is used to obtain the contour-ordered lattice Green's function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{G_{ij}(t,t^{\prime})=-i\langle\mathcal{T}d_{i}(t)d_{j}^{\dagger}(t^{\prime})\rangle}$
\end_inset

 from a Dyson equation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{ij}^{-1}(t,t')=(G_{0}^{-1})_{ij}(t,t')-\delta_{ij}\Sigma_{ii}(t,t')
\]

\end_inset

with the non-interacting lattice Green's function 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_{0}^{-1})_{ij}(t,t')$
\end_inset

.
 Like in the equilibrium case one has to solve the effective impurity action
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{\mathcal{\mathrm{S=i\int_{c}dtUn_{\uparrow}(t)n_{\downarrow}(t)-i\sum_{\sigma}\int_{c}dtdt^{\prime}d_{\sigma}^{\dagger}(t)\mathrm{\bigtriangleup}(t,t^{\prime})d_{\sigma}(t^{\prime})}}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma(t,t')$
\end_inset

 is implicitly defined via the Dyson equation of the impurity system.
 The set of equations for non-equilibirum DMFT is formally identical to
 the one for equilibrium DMFT with the crucial difference that all objects
 depend on two times.
 In the Dyson equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{ij}(t,t')$
\end_inset

 the self energy plays the role of a memory kernel.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Dyson equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In non-equilibrium DMFT all objects are two times functions and in order
 to solve the impurity problem, we need to solve Dyson equations of the
 form 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{\mathrm{\mathrm{\mathrm{G_{\alpha\alpha}(t,t')=G_{\alpha\alpha}^{(0)}(t,t')-\int_{0}^{t}dt_{1}\int_{0}^{t_{1}}dt_{2}G_{\alpha\alpha}^{(0)}(t,t_{1})\varSigma_{\alpha\alpha}(t_{1},t_{2})G_{\alpha\alpha}(t_{2},t')}}}}.
\]

\end_inset

These are Volterra integral equations of the second kind and they have a
 causal structure.
 
\end_layout

